WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.520
This module might genuinely change how you
perform in this role.

2
00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:09.420
Because here's the thing, the difference
between someone who's average on the phone and

3
00:00:09.420 --> 00:00:13.460
someone who consistently moves leads
forward, it's not the script.

4
00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:16.660
It's what happens when the seller pushes
back.

5
00:00:18.260 --> 00:00:20.100
Objections are not the enemy.

6
00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:22.300
They're actually a good sign.

7
00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:27.980
Think about it. If a seller truly had zero
interest in selling, they wouldn't bother

8
00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:29.420
pushing back on your price.

9
00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:32.220
They wouldn't say, I need to think about it.

10
00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:35.160
They just say, no thanks, and hang up.

11
00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:38.640
When someone objects, they're telling you
they're engaged.

12
00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:41.820
They have a concern sitting between them and
a yes.

13
00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:45.920
And your job is to figure out what it is and
address it.

14
00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:49.800
You need to rewire how you hear pushback.

15
00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:52.780
An objection is not a rejection.

16
00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:56.080
It's a conversation that still has momentum.

17
00:00:56.860 --> 00:00:59.980
They haven't hung up. They're still talking
to you.

18
00:01:00.165 --> 00:01:01.594
There's still something there.

19
00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:03.240
So how do you work with that?

20
00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:08.480
You hear the concern, you acknowledge it for
real, and you guide things forward.

21
00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:14.920
Not by being pushy, not by steamrolling,
just by being genuinely curious about

22
00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:16.660
what's actually going on.

23
00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:20.020
One more thing before we get into them.

24
00:01:20.420 --> 00:01:24.240
The objections you hear will depend on the
kind of call you're making.

25
00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:27.760
On cold outreach, you'll get more of the
defensive.

26
00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:30.940
Who are you pushback? How did you get my
number?

27
00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:34.840
I'm not interested. Stop calling me.

28
00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:41.000
When a lead has already been vetted and warmed
up, the objections shift toward the deal

29
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.880
itself. Price, timing, needing to talk to a
spouse.

30
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:51.140
Depending on your role, you'll live more in
one of those worlds than the other.

31
00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:57.600
But you need to be ready for all of it
because any objection can show up on any call.

32
00:01:58.463 --> 00:02:04.343
When you're on calls, you're going to hear
four types of responses, and they each need a

33
00:02:04.343 --> 00:02:05.248
different approach.

34
00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:11.040
The first is silence. You say something and
they just go quiet.

35
00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:14.000
Most people panic here and start rambling.

36
00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:15.620
Don't do that.

37
00:02:15.620 --> 00:02:20.140
Silence means they're processing what you
said, and that's a good thing.

38
00:02:20.780 --> 00:02:27.020
Give them the space. Whoever talks first
after a silence usually gives up ground,

39
00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:28.800
so just wait.

40
00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.060
The second is complaints.

41
00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:38.300
Stuff like, I'm tired of getting these calls,
or you people just want to lowball me.

42
00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:40.200
This isn't really an objection.

43
00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:41.620
It's venting.

44
00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:46.040
They're frustrated, probably from getting
hammered by other investors.

45
00:02:46.740 --> 00:02:50.180
Acknowledge it. Show some empathy and
redirect.

46
00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:55.540
Something like, I hear you, and I get that
you've probably gotten a lot of calls.

47
00:02:56.042 --> 00:02:58.757
I want to make sure this one is actually
worth your time.

48
00:02:59.262 --> 00:03:00.977
Can I ask you a couple of questions?

49
00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.960
The third type is what I call reactionary
defense responses.

50
00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:13.200
Things like, you've got two minutes, or just
make me an offer, or I've heard this

51
00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:15.220
before. These are automatic.

52
00:03:15.220 --> 00:03:20.260
It's like when you walk into a store and say,
just looking, even though you drove there

53
00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:21.820
specifically to buy something.

54
00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:26.980
Don't take the bait. Don't speed up your
process because they told you to hurry.

55
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:29.360
Just acknowledge it and keep moving.

56
00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:33.140
Totally understand. I'll be respectful of
your time.

57
00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.620
Let me ask you just a couple of quick things
so I can see if we can even help.

58
00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:41.680
And then there are real objections.

59
00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:43.660
Your price is too low.

60
00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:45.840
I need to talk to my wife.

61
00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:48.820
I want to list with a realtor first.

62
00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:54.700
These are genuine concerns, and they deserve
a real, thoughtful response.

63
00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.260
This is where the framework comes in.

64
00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:01.600
For every real objection, you use four
steps.

65
00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:08.240
First, you listen. And I mean actually listen,
not just wait for them to stop talking so

66
00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:09.680
you can deliver your rebuttal.

67
00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:11.620
Let them finish completely.

68
00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:14.280
Second, you acknowledge what they said.

69
00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:16.720
Show them you actually heard it.

70
00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:20.400
I completely understand why you'd feel that
way.

71
00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:22.960
Or, that makes total sense.

72
00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:26.520
Never dismiss what they're saying and never
argue.

73
00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:29.040
If you don't argue, you've lost.

74
00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:34.820
Third, instead of jumping into a
counterargument, you ask a question.

75
00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:40.880
If they say the price is too low, you ask,
what number were you hoping for?

76
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:45.320
If they say they need to think about it, you
ask, what specifically are you weighing?

77
00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:50.460
Questions give you information, and
information is how you actually solve problems.

78
00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:56.520
Fourth, you redirect. Once you understand
the real concern, you guide the conversation

79
00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:01.760
toward a solution. I hear you, and I want to
make sure we find something that works for

80
00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:02.660
both of us.

81
00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:07.220
Listen, acknowledge, ask, redirect.

82
00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:10.180
That sequence works for everything.

83
00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:16.940
The one thing you should absolutely never do
is treat an objection like a dead end.

84
00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:20.860
Every objection is a doorway into a deeper
conversation.

85
00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:25.560
Your job is not to overcome objections like
it's some kind of battle.

86
00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:27.260
It's to understand them.

87
00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:32.580
In your written reference materials, you'll
find a full objection guide with 28

88
00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:35.380
objections and specific rebuttals for each.

89
00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:41.040
Study them, practice them, but more
importantly, internalize the framework.

90
00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:47.820
Because if you really understand, listen,
acknowledge, ask, redirect, you can handle

91
00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:50.980
any objection, even ones you've never heard
before.

92
00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.900
Alright, more objection handling up next.

93
00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:58.260
Only this time, you're doing the talking.
